{"title_page": "Peter O'Rourke (U.S. government official)", "text_new": "{{About|the American government official|the Scottish footballer|Peter O'Rourke}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter O'Rourke Jr.\n| image = Peter O'Rourke official photo.jpg\n| office = Acting [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]]\n| order = \n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Thomas G. Bowman]]\n| term_start = May 29, 2018\n| term_end = July 30, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Robert Wilkie]] (acting)\n| successor = [[Robert Wilkie]]\n| birth_place = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|01|03}}\n| death_place = \n| death_date = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| education = [[University of Tennessee]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n| nickname = ROUR\n| allegiance = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch = {{flag|United States Navy}}<br>{{flag|United States Air Force}}\n| serviceyears = 1988\u20132002\n| rank = \n}}\n'''Peter O'Rourke''' is an American government official. He served as the acting [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]] and VA Chief of Staff under President [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web |author=United States Department of Veterans Affairs |title=Acting Secretary of Veterans Affairs |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |url=https://www.va.gov/opa/bios/secva.asp}}</ref> He previously worked in various positions in government consulting, including as a congressional staffer for U.S. Representative [[Tom Latham (politician)|Tom Latham]], and as an employee for CALIBRE Systems, and he also served as the executive director of the [[Republican Party of Florida]].\n\n==Education==\nO'Rourke graduated with a degree in political science from the [[University of Tennessee]] in 1998 and in logistics, materials and supply chain management from the [[Air Force Institute of Technology]] of the [[Air University (United States Air Force)|Air University]] in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.executivegov.com/2017/05/peter-orourke-to-serve-as-senior-adviser-executive-director-of-va-office-for-accountability-whistleblower-protection/|title=Peter O\u2019Rourke to Head VA Office for Accountability & Whistleblower Protection|date=May 15, 2017|website=Executive Gov}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nO'Rourke is a veteran of the [[United States Navy|Navy]] and [[United States Air Force|Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/veterans/2018/05/30/wilkie-steps-down-as-acting-va-secretary-top-deputy-retires/|title=Big changes for VA\u2019s leadership|author=Shane|first=Leo,  III|date=May 30, 2018|work=Military.com|access-date=}}</ref> He held various leadership roles with Calibre Systems, the Association of the U.S. Army, Blackland Aerospace, Strong America Now, Accenture, and George Group Consulting.\n\n=== Department of Veterans Affairs ===\nIn May 2017, O'Rourke began work within the [[United States Department of Veteran Affairs|Department of Veterans Affairs]] as the executive director for VA's Office of Accountability and Whistleblower Protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.disabledveterans.org/2018/05/31/advice-peter-orourke-ex-calibre-exec-turned-acting-va-secretary/|title=Advice For Peter O\u2019Rourke, Ex-CALIBRE Exec Turned Acting VA Secretary|author=Krause, Benjamin|accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nHe was appointed by President [[Donald Trump]] to serve as the chief of staff of the VA on February 16, 2018, where he was key to the passage of the VA MISSION Act of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |author=United States Department of Veterans Affairs |title=Peter O\u2019Rourke Senior Executive Biography |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |url=https://www.va.gov/opa/bios/docs/orourke.pdf}}</ref> The bill allocated $55 billion toward providing veterans with more private healthcare options.<ref>{{cite news |author=Military.com |title=Trump Signs $55 Billion Bill to Replace VA Choice Program |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2018/06/06/trump-signs-55-billion-bill-replace-va-choice-program.html}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018, O'Rourke was appointed by President Trump to serve as the Acting Secretary of Veterans Affairs while [[Robert Wilkie]] awaited Senate confirmation to serve in the position in a permanent capacity.<ref>{{cite news |author=POLITICO |title=Trump taps O\u2019Rourke as acting VA secretary ahead of Wilkie confirmation |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/30/trump-peter-orourke-veterans-affairs-611647}}</ref> O'Rourke was chosen over Deputy Secretary [[Thomas G. Bowman|Thomas Bowman]], who announced his retirement in June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |author=Stars and Stripes |title=VA leadership shuffle: Secretary steps down, chief of staff moves up, deputy retires |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/va-leadership-shuffle-secretary-steps-down-chief-of-staff-moves-up-deputy-retires-1.530117}}</ref> Wilkie was sworn in as Secretary of the VA on July 30, 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/robert-wilkie-sworn-veterans-affairs-secretary/story?id=56924300|title=Robert Wilkie sworn in as new Veterans Affairs secretary|last=Ebbs|first=Stephanie|date=July 30, 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, O'Rourke was forced to resign his position as VA senior advisor after the White House was told he was doing little work but still getting paid.<ref>{{cite magazine | last1=Biery | first1=Maria | title=VA senior adviser forced to resign after months of getting paid to do no work | url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/va-senior-adviser-forced-to-resign-after-months-of-getting-paid-to-do-no-work | date=December 12, 2018 | magazine=[[Washington Examiner]] | accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Rein | first1=Lisa | last2=Dawsey | first2=Josh | title=Trump loyalist at VA forced out after collecting pay but doing little work | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/there-were-times-i-didnt-have-a-lot-to-do-trump-loyalist-at-va-forced-out-after-collecting-pay-but-doing-little-work/2018/12/11/26e4704a-fcb7-11e8-ad40-cdfd0e0dd65a_story.html | date=December 11, 2018 | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, the Inspector General of the VA reported that O'Rourke had used his power as head of the whistleblower office to end investigations into allies, and that he had failed to provide basic reports to Congress on the office\u2019s operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/veterans-affairs-investigators-fault-whistleblower-office-created-by-trump-11571925164|title=Veterans Affairs Investigators Fault Whistleblower Office Created by Trump|last=Kesling|first=Ben|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trumps-heralded-whistleblower-office-at-va-has-failed-its-most-basic-mission-watchdog-says/2019/10/24/561e9022-f679-11e9-8cf0-4cc99f74d127_story.html|title=Trump\u2019s heralded whistleblower office at VA is failing in its most basic mission, watchdog says|last=Rein|first=Lisa|date=October 24, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2019/10/24/florida-gop-official-accused-of-misdeeds-and-retaliation-while-at-va-1225979|title=Florida GOP official accused of 'misdeeds' and retaliation while at VA|first=Matt|last=Dixon|website=Politico PRO}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.floridaphoenix.com/blog/reports-newly-picked-fl-republican-party-director-had-troubles-in-washington/|title=Reports: Newly picked FL Republican Party director had troubles in Washington|first=Julie|last=Hauserman}}</ref>\n\n=== Florida Republican Party ===\nIn August 2019, O'Rourke was appointed as the executive director of the [[Republican Party of Florida|Florida Republican Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/6d21566c4855489a9c605f4c3964d379|title=Former Trump official to helm Florida Republican Party|date=August 26, 2019|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> Some Florida Republicans criticized his running of the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://floridapolitics.com/archives/309996-florida-gop-leaders-begin-calling-for-peter-orourkes-ouster|title=Florida GOP leaders begin calling for Peter O\u2019Rourke\u2019s ousting|first=Jacob|last=Ogles|date=October 31, 2019}}</ref> O'Rourke announced he would resign from his position in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://floridapolitics.com/archives/321551-executive-director-peter-orourke-exiting-florida-gop|title=Executive director Peter O\u2019Rourke leaving Florida GOP|first=Peter|last=Schorsch|date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|peterorourke02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Wilkie]]<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Acting [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]]|years=May 29, 2018 \u2013 July 30, 2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Wilkie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orourke, Peter}}\n[[Category:United States Air Force airmen]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Veterans Affairs officials]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States congressional aides]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the American government official|the Scottish footballer|Peter O'Rourke}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name = Peter O'Rourke Jr.\n| image = Peter O'Rourke official photo.jpg\n| office = Acting [[United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs]]\n| order = \n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Thomas G. Bowman]]\n| term_start = May 29, 2018\n| term_end = July 30, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Robert Wilkie]] (ac